<br>
The &quot;Where the good jobs are going thread&quot; started out about how higher skilled jobs are being exported to India, but quickly devolved into an immigration debate, then a political one.  The original crux of the thread was never really coverd IMO.<br>
<br>
A brief recap:  One of the newest cost saving strategies many companies are using is to move higher skilled jobs such as customer service, technical support, and even accounting services out of the United States to India, where there is an excess of cheap skilled labor.  This has resulted in some significant overhead reductions for the firms that have done so, and it looks to be a trend that will continue.  The boardrooms are happy, but American workers are not, so much so that there are now several Congressmen and Senators making rumblings about it.<br>
<br>
Now, my question is:  Are these job-exporting companies being short-sighted?  Is there a danger that in the long term that should enough of these higher-skilled, higher-paying jobs go to India that eventually there may be a reduction in the US customer base for these services if there aren't enough higher-paying jobs to pay for them? <br>
<br>
I'll admit I'm curious, since the loss of much of the US manufacturing capability led to the shift to our current &quot;service oriented&quot; economy.  As has been mentioned before, many people migrated to higher-skilled jobs in response to that earlier trend.  What could happen now that we are exporting some of those higher-skilled jobs?  Where will the people who lost those jobs go? <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=187084"><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Colphax Moonleaf</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
